LEARNING_OUTCOMES:
development of communicative abilities in a foreign language;
   getting to know oneself;
   support of autonomous learning.

Studying the course will enable students
   understand texts and lectures by a native speaker on economic-historical topics;
   explain the root causes, developing and consequences of economic crises.

Students will:
   - be able to communicate in common situations at the university and in everyday life at a basic level;
   - gain knowledge about the Czech culture and society.

OBJECTIVES:
After the course, students will be able to:
   Identify and comprehend conversation situations and reproduce conversation schemes in basic conversation situations given by the textbook;
   Apply the conversation schemes and acquired vocabulary to other interactive conversation situations;
   Read and write basic conversation texts given in the textbook;
   Apply acquired grammar, vocabulary and increase necessary reading and writing comprehension.

LEARNING_OUTCOMES:
After completing the course the student will:
   - understand how the multilingual mind works;
   - have acquired basic socio-cultural competences;
   - be able to communicate safely in multilingual communication situations.

After completion of the course the student will be able to:
   - identify problematic areas of grammar and spelling of Czech as a second language;
   - perceive the possible influence of other languages on Czech as a second language;
   - navigate through available teaching materials and platforms;
   - use new knowledge to improve communication in Czech as a second language, especially in a university environment.

After completion of the course the student will be able to:
   - identify important features of Czech language in preschool children;
   - understand the specifics of communication with a pediatric patient;
   - apply the acquired knowledge in practice.

After completing the course the student will:
   - be able to communicate better in Czech as a second language, especially in a university environment;
   - have functional language relevant to the academic environment and field of study;
   - have a better understanding of the cultural context in which they are situated.

Upon completion of the course, the student will be able to:
   - explain the principles of modern technologies used in biological and biomedical research;
   - understand basic principles of methods for studying the structure and function of biomolecules, including sequencing, proteomics, NMR spectroscopy, crystallography, and microscopy;
   - understand basic principles of interpretation of experimental data obtained from different life science techniques;
   - compare the advantages and limitations of different methods and select the appropriate approach for solving specific research problems;
   - design experimental strategies for studying biological systems.

Upon completion of the course, the student will be able to:
   - recognise formal and informal register;
   - apply vocabulary development strategies;
   - build their academic vocabulary through word building ;

After completing the course, students:
   - will be capable of recognising potential causes of culturally based complications in communication and of acting appropriately in simple everyday exchanges;
   - can generally respond to the most commonly used cultural cues, act according to socio-pragmatic conventions and explain or discuss features of their own and other cultures;
   - are usually able to recognise and repair misunderstandings.

OBJECTIVES:
The aim of this course is to provide participants with useful sets of study materials, as well as with a variety of diverse methodologies and strategies that will help them:
   - improve their plurilingual and pluricultural competences at A2-B1 level of CEFR while adopting intercomprehension and mediation strategies;
   - reflect on languages and cultures in order to learn how to use efficiently their personal linguistic repertoire, ie. languages they already master at different levels; thanks to this participants are able to understand languages they have not learnt in formal education, nor they have not learnt them at all;
   - foster their cultural awareness and develop their cultural intelligence.

LEARNING_OUTCOMES:
After completing the course, participants:
   - will be aware of their plurilingual repertoire and they will know how to further develop it;
   - will be capable to recognise internationalisms and words/signs common to different languages to deduce the meaning of simple signs and notices and to identify the probable message of a short, simple text or speech;
   - will acquire basic key words for typical situations (routine situations) so they can concentrate on them while trying to understand to the probable meaning;
   - will be able to work with gestures and mimics which considerably helps to understand the overall meaning of situation and they will be able to recognise when difficulties occur in interaction with members of other cultures;
   - will get familiar with the concept of otherness and understand that different cultures may have different practices and norms, actions may be perceived differently by people belonging to other cultures.

Upon course completion, the student will be able to:
   - describe different types of graphs, analyze the data they display, and communicate it to other users;
   - break down text into logical units and link them through connectors;
   - recognize the main ideas in  text and summarize them;
   - mediate information from a  dense text using clarifications and examples.

After completing the course, participants will:

   - Be familiar with several new perspectives on reading, conceiving, structuring, writing, and revising academic texts in English;
   - Be able to identify a few specific techniques professionals use to make their writing clear, concise, and engaging;
   - Be well-practiced in adapting these techniques to their own writing;
   - Be introduced to the Masaryk University Writing Lab and its one-on-one writing consultation services

After completing the course the student will:
   - be able to orient herself/himself in Brno;
   - be able to use the knowledge gained in the course in practical and everyday life;
   - be able to find his/her way around the academic environment, especially at Masaryk University;
   - be familiar with the cultural and sporting highlights;
   - be able to better understand the life and rhythm of Czech society;
   - feel more comfortable in his new place of work or study;
   - be able to integrate more easily into Czech society.
